Predicting Wine Taste Preferences¶

This workspace is used to critically analyse the wine data in order to determine if the wine tastes 'good' or 'bad'. Minor EDA was conducted to determine some relationships between variables and possible extreme values. The model to predict the wine quality was built using three different approaches, forward stepwise, ridge and lasso.

The format of the data is a csv, where the Wine_training.csv was used as the training set and Wine_testing.csv was used as the test set. Cross validation was performed and using both predictive accuracy and area under curve as a measurement of predictive performance.

The best model was compared by testing it on the training set to get the predictive performance.

ggplot2, reshape2, e1071 and gridextra - used to plot graphs and arrange it

ROCR - calculate the AUC for prediction performance

glmnet and boot - perform lasso and ridge regression

Skewness¶

A sorted list of the skewness of the dataset is represented as shown above along with the distribution histogram. The data with a skewness closests to 0 represents a normal distribution and those that are positively further away are tend to be right skewed.

Discoveries from boxplot and histogram¶

From both the boxplot, and the histgram and skewness, the following information are discovered:

  • Fixed acidity (Approximately normally distributed) - There are some points that could be outliers, hence the approximate normally distributed, however not to the extreme. Most of the wine has a fixed acidity distributed between 6 and 7
  • Volatile acidity (Approximately normally distributed) - The peak of the histogram shows that in most cases, the wine has a volatile acidity of approximately 0.25 to 0.3 with some minor outliers shown in boxplot, it is approximately normally distributed
  • Citric acid (Edge peak) - Has a peak on the right side, could be caused due to the data being lumped together at approximately 0.5
  • Residual sugar (Right skewed) - The histogram and skewness showed that it is highly right skewed, with a long tail on the left, where the boxplot shows an existance of an extreme value being above the level of 60. A lot of the wine have a sugar level of around 6

  • Chlorides (Right skewed) - Lots of the points lie within the outer range of the upper limit of the quantile, with some value that could be considered as an extreme value and outlier. This caused the distribution to have a long right tail, hence right skewed

  • Free sulfur dioxide (Right skewed) - Boxplot shows an extreme value, most likely to have caused the distribution to be right skewed. The value could be potential outlier

  • Total sulfur dioxide (Normal Distribution) - Most of the total sulfur dioxide level are within the range of 100 and 150 as shown in the histogram. Although boxplot shows some extreme values and values that are in the outer range of the quantile, the distribution is still likely to be normal
  • Density (Right skewed) - Boxplot shows an extreme value and possible outlier. Caused the histogram to be right skewed
  • pH (Comb distribution) - The rounding of the pH level caused the histogram to be combed shape, although it looks like it's normally distributed
  • Sulphates (Comb distribution) - It is a comb distributon in which the boxplot shows values that lie withn the outer range and some extreme values, however they might not be outlier as they are tight together
  • Alcohol (Multimodal distribution) - Alcohol is considered as a multimodal distribution as it has several normal distribution that were combined, hence the top of the distribution resembles a plateau. Boxplot shows no values outside the range or any extreme values. Hence the distribution is considered to be distribution evenly on the lower and the uppper range

Distribution type from http://asq.org/learn-about-quality/data-collection-analysis-tools/overview/histogram2.html

Relationship between attributes¶

Summary of findings in relationship¶

  • There are strong relationship between density and residual sugar, this makes sense as the solution residual of sugar increases the viscosity of wine
  • Strong negative correlation between density and alcohol, this is reasonable as the more alcoholic the drink the less the density of the wine as the chemical compound for alcohol is saturated
  • As free sulfur dioxide increaes it would contribute to the total sulfur dioxide, hence some correlation exists between them.
  • There are also some correlation between total sulfur dioxide and density. The additional chemical composition of sulfur dioxide increases the density of the wine.

Function - Multivaraible scatterplot¶

In [8]:
create_scatter <- function(dataset, Wine.Quality, xVar, yVar, xName, yName, title, lLim, ULim, lim) #setting formal parameter of function
    {
        #create scatter plot, uses wine quality as the third variable
        plot <- ggplot(data = dataset, aes(x = xVar, y = yVar)) + geom_point(aes(color = factor(Wine.Quality)))
        plot <- plot + xlab(xName) + ylab(yName) + ggtitle(title) #adds title and labels
        plot <- plot + scale_color_manual(values = c("blue", "purple")) #sets the colour of the factor
        plot <- plot + scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(lLim, ULim, by = lim))
        plot <- plot + theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=90, hjust=1))
        return(plot)
}

Summary: Good quality wine tends to have a lower form of density but higher alcohol level. Nevertheless the total sulfur dioxide level and free sulfur dioxide is also within 50 to 200 and 10 to 50 respectively.

The use of logistic regression:¶

Logistic regression was used as it is able to classify binary style response varaible. Hence the probability of either bad or good using logistic regression is only between 0 and 1.

Summary of full mode:¶

Fixed Acidity, citric acid, chlorides and total suflur dioxide - The absolute z value is rather small, hence the p-value is greater than 0.05. This indicates that these predictors should be excluded from the model in determining the probability of the wine being good or bad.

The Null deviance at 4194, is the score of the goodness of the model in which only the intercept are included. It shows how well the quality of the wine was predicted by the model, including only the intercept, which is the grand mean. The variance based on this model would be low, however the model is highly bias and would produce significant test error.

The Residual deviance - Full Model, the score of the model with all inputed predictors, is 3227.2, hence it is lower than the null deviance. This shows that the model with all the predictors explains the data better than the model with just the intercept. However the trade off is that the model is highly complexed. Although there is a reduce in bias from this, however the variance based on this model would be very high along with the test error.

#function to create the confusion matrix of the prediction
confuse_matrix <- function(model, response) {
    pred <- predict(model, type = 'response') #predict using the 
    pred_mod <- rep('bad', length(pred)) #assigns all prediction as bad
    pred_mod[pred > 0.5] <- 'good' #set all prediction greater than 0.5 to good - cutpoint
    table(pred_mod, response) #put values in a table
}

Function - Prediction accuracy¶

In [13]:
correct_pred <- function(model, response, test_set){
    pred <- predict(model, type = 'response', test_set)
    pred_mod <- rep('bad', length(pred))
    pred_mod[pred > 0.5] <- 'good'
    result <- mean(pred_mod == response) #calculates the mean of all prediction that is reference to the quality
    return(result * 100) #returns the mean as a percentage to 2 decimal points
}

Overall the full model predicted only 75.27% correctly. By analysing the confusion matrix, it can be seen that the binary classifier - logistic, identified the wine default, which is 'good', as being 'bad' and wine that are 'bad' as being 'good'. The logistic regression predicted that a total of 2393 were default, however only 1896 was identified as being true positive, this is equivalent to 79.23%. However the 2178 wine that defaulted were missed by 282, equivalent to 12.95%, wines that defaulted maybe be unacceptable.

Sensitivity and specificity is important to the prediction of binary value, the 'good' and 'bad' wines. In this case of sensitivity, the percentage of true defaulters, 'good' wines being identified is high at 87.05%. The specificity is identified as non-defaulters that are correctly identified, hence 'bad' wines identified as 'good', which is 55.02%. Hence, the logistic regression does a good job identifying the true defaulters, however does not do a great job at identifying 'bad' wines being 'good'

Using step function to perform forward stepwise on the whole dataset¶

Previously the whole training dataset and predictors of wine was used to build a full model. However this model is highly bias as it contains all predictors of wine, although leading to a higher ressidual sum of squares, but this is an approach to determine how well the model fits the training data, but not the real world. Hence the model was most likely overfitting, favouring training error rather than test error. Cross validation using 10 folds will be used to reduce bias and variance of the model.

Summary¶

Akaike Information Criterion (AIC) forward stepwise

Forward stepwise based model selection used AIC to determine which variable to include in the model by building the model up from a null model. AIC was used as a criteria to choose the optimal model. The forward stepwise chose eight predictors, ~alcohol + volatile acidity + residual sugar + fixed acidity + free sulfur dioxide + sulphates + density + pH.

Bayesian Information Criterion (BIC) forward stepwise

adjusting the k to log(n), changes the stepwise function to using BIC as the measurement. The predictors, ~ alcohol + volatile.acidity + residual.sugar + fixed.acidity + sulphates + free.sulfur.dioxide, were chosen by compairing the BIC and choosing amongst the model, the model with the lowest BIC, through the process of building the model by adding one variable at a time from a null model.

Analysis

The difference between the model selected by the AIC and BIC differs in the number of predictors used and the type of predictors. AIC differs from BIC as it had also used density and pH, hence consists of 8 predictors, whereas BIC only has 6 predictors. Both methods uses the concept of maximum likelihood estimates and penalizing the free parameters to combat overfitting, however both AIC and BIC produced different results in terms of final model due to the fact that the number of observation is large. BIC applies more penalty to complex models, causing BIC to produce a model with less predictors than AIC. The model from AIC will likely be more acceptable as BIC simply just reduces the maximum likelihood sleection due to the number of parameters being equal to the model's interest.

Using Cross validation

Although the number of predictors have been reduced along with the decrease in bias, but an increase in variance, cross validation using 10-folds will be used to support the selection of the variables that should be included in the final model. Using the whole data is highly bias towards the model selection. Using the cross validation then computing the predictive accuracy and AUC are better representation of the model's ability to predict a real world case, on an unseen data. Hence, in context it is the direct estimate of the test error, however in case of the logistic regression it is a representation of the prediction of the performance of the model's prediction.

#function to perform cross validation, allows the selection of which fold and the required data set
cv_set <- function(number_of_folds, fold_number, dataset, set_name){
    set.seed(1234)
    shuffled_data <- dataset[sample(nrow(dataset)),] #reshuffles the data
    folds <- rep_len(1:number_of_folds,nrow(shuffled_data)) #creates the fold on the shuffled data
    data_fold <- which(folds == fold_number) #subsets the data
    train_set <- shuffled_data[-data_fold,] #creating training set
    test_set <- shuffled_data[data_fold,] #creating test set
    if(set_name == "train"){ return(train_set)} #returns training set
    else if (set_name == "test"){return(test_set)} #returns the test set
}

Function - Area under curve¶

In [18]:
auc_roc <- function(model, dataset, type){
    prediction_auc <- predict(model, newdata = dataset, type = 'response') #creates list of predictions on a dataset
    pred <- prediction(prediction_auc, dataset$quality)
    auc_plot <- performance(pred, measure = 'tpr', x.measure = 'fpr') #assigns specificity and sensitivity
    auc <- performance(pred, measure = 'auc')@y.values[[1]] #computes the AUC then convert to vector space
    if(type == 'auc'){return(auc)}
    else if(type == 'plot'){return(auc_plot)}
}

Function - Model Cross Validation¶

In [19]:
#function to perform 10 cross validations on certain combination of response variable and the predictor/s
cross_model_10 <- function(response_n_predictors, type){
    pred_acc <- NULL #initiates a list
    auc <- NULL
    for(i in 1:10){ #10 folds
        train_set <- cv_set(10, i, wine, 'train') #calls the cross validation function, pulls out training set 1st fold
        test_set <- cv_set(10, i, wine, 'test')
        model <- glm(paste(response_n_predictors), data = train_set, family = binomial) #creates model based on input
        pred <- correct_pred(model, test_set$quality, test_set) #calls in the predictive accuracy function on the test
        auc_calc <- auc_roc(model, test_set, 'auc')
        auc <- c(auc, auc_calc)
        pred_acc <- c(pred_acc, pred) #appends the calculated prediction accuracy on the intiated list
    }
    if(type == "pa"){ return(mean(pred_acc))} #returns training set
    else if (type == "auc"){return((mean(auc)*100))} #returns the test set
}

Function - Model Selection Cross Validation¶

In [20]:
#function to add a predictor to the inputed model and calculate the cross validation error (prediction accuracy)
model_selection_cv <- function(current_model, list_of_used_predictors, measurement){
    model_list <- NULL
    model_name <- NULL
    model_auc <- NULL
    flt_wine <- within(wine, rm(list=list_of_used_predictors)) #filters data on variables that was already used
    if(length(names(flt_wine)) > 0){ #process if there is still variables to be added
        for(i in 1:length(names(flt_wine))){ #iterates though the column names of the data
            temp_model <- paste(current_model, '+', names(flt_wine[i])) #adds in the one variable to the current
            model_name <- c(model_name, temp_model) #add model name to a list
            model_list <- c(model_list, cross_model_10(temp_model, 'pa')) #add the prediction accuracy to a list
            model_auc <- c(model_auc, cross_model_10(temp_model, 'auc')) #adds AUC to list
        }
        frame <- data.frame(model_name, model_list, model_auc) #puts the model name and prediction accuracy to a dataframe
        colnames(frame) <- c('Model', 'Prediction_Accuracy', 'AUC') #rename column of dataframe
        if(measurement == 'pa'){
            #prints out model with higher prediction accuracy
            print(as.character(frame$Model[frame$Prediction_Accuracy == max(frame$Prediction_Accuracy)]))
            print(paste('Predictive Accuracy: ', 
                        frame$Prediction_Accuracy[frame$Prediction_Accuracy == max(frame$Prediction_Accuracy)]))
            frame
        } else if (measurement == 'auc') {
            print(as.character(frame$Model[frame$AUC == max(frame$AUC)])) #shows the model with highest AUC
            print(paste('AUC: ', frame$AUC[frame$AUC == max(frame$AUC)])) #prints AUC
            frame
        } else if (measurement == 'both') {
            print(as.character(frame$Model[(frame$Prediction_Accuracy == max(frame$Prediction_Accuracy)) &
                                           (frame$AUC == max(frame$AUC))]))
            print(paste('Predictive Accuracy: ', 
            frame$Prediction_Accuracy[frame$Prediction_Accuracy == max(frame$Prediction_Accuracy)]))
            print(paste('AUC: ',  frame$AUC[frame$AUC == max(frame$AUC)]))
            frame
        }
    }else{print("You've already added all the features in")}
}

Model selection using 10 folds cross validation¶

Two types of cross validation errors are used, predictive accuracy and AUC. Each variables will be added to the formula and the validation errors of each specific formula with the added variable will be cross validated on a 10 fold in which the error will be averaged. Each variables will be cross validated.

Descriptions:¶

The process of selecting a final model was aided through 10-folds cross validation using the forward stepwise approach. All of the variables was added to the base model each time, and 10-folds cross validation was applied to produce a mean prediction accuracy/AUC, values allocating to certain variable is added to the model. Process repeats until the null model becomes a full model.

A model was built using AUC and prediction accuracy as the unit of measure. The first 4 variables that was added to the null model, 'alcohol', 'volatile acidity', 'residual sugar' and 'citric acid', have the highest prediction accuracy and AUC, when added independently. The stepwise was split into two category, AUC and predictive accuracy after the 5th and so forth variables were added, as when a variable may be rank the best according to it having the highest predictive accuracy, but it did not have the highest AUC.

The one-standard-error-rule will be applied to both predictive accuracy and AUC models to determine which model in each method are suitable model to be the final model. This method works by identifying the prediction accuracy or AUC that is within 1 standard error of the mean of the prediction accuracy or AUC, respectively. If they are within, and the model is less complex, that model is to be used as the final model as it is not significantly different from the more complex model with a little higher prediction accuracy or AUC.

Best model using predictive accuracy¶

As shown in the plot, as more variables are added to the model, the predictive accuracy increased but decreased after the addition of the 7th predictor. Due to this decrease it can easily be seen that the model with the 5 variables tend to be the one that performs the best on the 10 folds cross validation training set, in accordance to the predictive accuracy, 76.27, which is also the same as when the full model was used on the whole dataset. Final model from this is:

quality ~ alcohol + volatile.acidity + residual.sugar + fixed.acidity + citric.acid

Best model using AUC¶

As shown in the plot based, the AUC tends to increase as more variables are added. However as the complexity of the model increases passes the point where 8 predictors were used, it starts to slightly decrease. It is necessarily to use the one-standard-error-rule. As the AUC for each models seemed closely related. The model with a size of 5 has an AUC within 1 standard error of the highest AUC, which is based on the 8 predictor model. Hence, the model with 5 predictors will be used as the final model from AUC.

quality ~ alcohol + volatile.acidity + residual.sugar + fixed.acidity + sulphates

Selecting final model¶

What both models generated from using predictive accuracy and AUC have in common is that they both have the predictors 'alcohol', 'volatile acidity', 'residual sugar', 'fixed acidity' and 'density'. Refering back to the multi-relationship scatter plot, it can be seen that there are some correlations with density and residual sugar, and density and alcohol. Both of these two relationship have the highest correlation amongst other predictors. Hence, contributing to whether it will increase the probability of the quality being good or bad. However, the number of predictors for both of these models are the same, differ slightly to the fact that in predictive accuracy, citric acid was used and this was replaced with sulphate for the AUC approach.

Although the measurement of predictive accuracy is more intuitive, however it is was based on a cutpoint of 50%, however the best cutpoint is to be determined from finding the cutpoint that is closests to the probability of actually true. Hence it could be that the cutpoint is not actually 50%, the the case where 95% of the wine are actually good, then cutpoint would instead be 5% for the bad wines. However the overall accuracy of the model varies from different cutpoints. Reciever Operating Characteristic (ROC), takes into consideration of both specificity and sensitivity, and trying all the cutpoints, where this is given by the Area Under Curve (AUC). In this case of identifying if the wine is bad or good, the AUC provides more information on the probability of predicting if the wine is bad or good, as oppose to using the predictive to determine if the wine is just good, and assigning bad to the rest that is lower than the cutpoint.

To conclude, the best model in this case is the 8 predictor model from AUC:

quality ~ alcohol + volatile.acidity + residual.sugar + fixed.acidity + sulphates

Different from stepwise approach on the whole dataset¶

This formula has less number of predictors than the forward stepwise method that was based on the whole dataset, that was based on both AIC and BIC. The formula is a lot smaller, where the the AIC approach produced a model with 8 predictors and the BIC had 6 predictors. The reduced in model complexity reduces the level of bias.

Using the shrinkage method¶

Shrinkage method is the process of using all predictors but regularising the coefficient estimates of each predictors, hence shrinking the coefficient towards 0, consequently reducing the variance of the model. Two types, Ridge (L2 Regularization), and lasso (L1 Regularization). Lasso performs model selection as it reduces the number of coefficient unlike ridge.

Lasso and ridge are used over OLS (ordinary least square) as the aim of the procedure is to determine model that performs the best on an unseen dataset, hence if OLS were to be used, it would lead to higher chance of overfitting, high prediction error.

label_plot <- function(fit) {
        length_lam <- length(fit$lambda)
        forlbls <- log(fit$lambda[length_lam])
        coeff <- fit$beta[, length_lam]
        text(forlbls, coeff, labels = names(coeff), cex = 0.5)
        legend('bottomright', lty = 1, legend = names(coeff), col = 1:length(names(coeff)), cex = .7)
         #creates name for line, resets the size of the legend box
    }
#function to produce plot
pltcoef_las_rdg <- function(o_l, choice, ylim){
    wine_mat <- model.matrix(quality ~., data = wine)[,-1] 
    fit_reg <- glmnet(wine_mat, wine$quality, alpha = o_l, family = 'binomial') #fits ridge/lasso model
    plot(fit_reg, xvar = choice, col = 1:dim(coef(fit_reg))[1], label = TRUE, ylim = c(ylim, 2)) #plots model, assign color
    label_plot(fit_reg) #adds in labels for the model
}

Lasso Plots

Summary¶

Both of the coefficient for Ridge and Lasso was plotted against the log of lambda, which is the weight given to the regularization term for ridge and lasso. As previously mentioned, ridge penalises the least significant coefficients and shrinks it towards 0 and lasso reduces the coefficient to 0. The model was developed on a value grid of approximately 100 values of lambda. As lambda increases, the coefficients are more regularised hence approach or reaching 0, and vice versa.

Both type of plots as indicated above showed different coloured lines that is referenced to the different predictors. They provide similar information, but on a different scale.

Ridge¶

Since Ridge regression penalises the coefficients by shrinking it towards 0, the least important predictors' coefficient will shrinking faster than the more important predictors. In the plot, as the lambda increases, chance of the resulting the probability of 1, which indicates 'good' quality, decreases. Predictors such as chloride, density and volatile acidity shrunk the slowest, as indicated by the first plot, where the line was sparsed widely at the bottom, this indicated that it took a lot of weight of regularization to shrink those coefficient, hence these predictors are most likely to be important to the model. However since ridge retains all predictors, the plot showed that all predictors ended up being close to 0 after the log lambda of 4 was applied.

Lasso¶

Another plot, along with the log lambda, was added for the Lasso, that is the L1 norm. In the case of the lambda plot, as lambda approaches 0, the most important predictors' coefficient reached 0. In this case predictors such as volatile acidity, alcohol, sulphate and fixed acidity required a lot of regularization weight on the coefficients in order for it to become 0, hence it showed that they are likley to be important to the mode.

The L1 norm, represents the regularization term, where lambda was used as the weight of the term. Or simply the maximum permission value that the L1 norm can take. Hence a small L1 norm (vector space), represents an empty model. As the norm increaes, predictors can join the norm with their coefficients. Predictors that joined the norm early are considered to be relevant to relevant to the response varaible, hence the overall model. Predictors that joins later than others, such as chlorides are less likely to be important to the model.

Conclusion¶

Overall, in order to determine the best model to generate the probability of wine qualities, cross validation, such as 10-folds, within the generalised linear model needs to be considered.

las_ridge <- function(dataset, response, o_l, return_type){
    set.seed(135)
    wine_mat <- model.matrix(quality ~., data = dataset)[, -1] # converts to matrix form
    cv_reg <- cv.glmnet(wine_mat, response, alpha = o_l, family = 'binomial') #performs cv to find best lambda
    fit_reg <- glmnet(wine_mat, response, alpha = o_l, family = 'binomial')
    pred <- predict(fit_reg, s = cv_reg$lambda.min, type = "coefficients")[1:12, ] #prediction using best lambda, get coef
    if(return_type == 'coef'){return(cv_reg)}
    else if (return_type == 'table'){return(pred)}
    else if (return_type == 'fit'){return(fit_reg)}
}

Seed¶

The seed was set to be 135, this made sure that when the result were reproduced, the same result would show. However it should be noted that the coefficiens of the predictors in lasso and ridge fluactuates depending on the minimum lambda value generated by 10 folds cross validation. If the same seed is not used the coefficient value would vary, but slightly, still indicating which predictors are mostly affected by the regularization term.

Coefficient table and plot¶

Although in Ridge all predictors are chosen, however predictors such as free sulfure dioxide, total sulfure dioxide and residual sugar, are heavily penalised by the regularization, hence having the lowest coefficients when compared to other variables.

In lasso, citric acid, and density are heavily penalised to 0, and predictors' coefficient such as total sulfur dioxide and free sulfur dioxide are insignificant. These coefficients varies with the cross validation. The seed was set so that the result is static, however the main concept is the penalty that lambda has on the regularisation of each predictors.

This showed that lasso selected only 9 varaibles as the predictors for the best model. This can also be seen on the lasso plot, where the second vertical line is marked on the lasso plot. The plot showed that a model with 7 predictors is within one standard error of the mean of all model (second dashed line), hence it is likely that the least significant predictors, as denoted by its coefficient, did not affect the model's power in predicting. This leaves the model with approximately 7 predictors in total that are important to the model.

cv_best_model2 <- function(resp_pred, alphatype){
    pred_acc <- NULL #initiates a list
    for(i in 1:10){ #10 folds
        train_set <- cv_set(10, i, wine, 'train') 
        test_set <- cv_set(10, i, wine, 'test')
        
        if(length(resp_pred) > 0){ #checks if there anything in first parameter of the function
            model <- glm(paste(resp_pred), data = train_set, family = 'binomial') #pastes the formular into log function
            pred <- auc_roc(model, test_set, 'auc') #calculates predictive accuracy
            pred_acc <- c(pred_acc, pred) #stores the value in a list
        } else if (alphatype == 1 | alphatype == 0){
            
            x <- model.matrix(quality ~ ., data = train_set)[, -1]
            cv_glm <- cv.glmnet(x, train_set$quality, alpha = alphatype, family = 'binomial') 
            bestlam <- cv_glm$lambda.min
            glm_output <- glmnet(x, train_set$quality, alpha = alphatype, family = 'binomial')
            x2 <- model.matrix(quality ~ ., data = test_set)[,-1]
            
            las_ridge_pred <- predict(glm_output, s = bestlam, newx = x2) 
            
            pred <- prediction(las_ridge_pred, test_set$quality)
            auc <- performance(pred, measure = 'auc')@y.values[[1]] #uses AUC as measurement, converts to vector space
            pred_acc <- c(pred_acc, auc)
        }
    }
    return(mean(pred_acc)*100)
}

single_auc_final <- function(resp_pred, alphatype, trainingSet, testingSet){
    if(length(resp_pred) > 0){
        model <- glm(paste(resp_pred), data = trainingSet, family = 'binomial') #pastes the formular into log function
        pred <- auc_roc(model, testingSet, 'auc') #calculates predictive accuracy
        return(pred)
    } else if (alphatype == 1 | alphatype == 0){
        x <- model.matrix(quality ~ ., data = trainingSet)[, -1]
        cv_glm <- cv.glmnet(x, trainingSet$quality, alpha = alphatype, family = 'binomial') 
        bestlam <- cv_glm$lambda.min
        glm_output <- glmnet(x, trainingSet$quality, alpha = alphatype, family = 'binomial')
        x2 <- model.matrix(quality ~ ., data = testingSet)[,-1]
        las_ridge_pred <- predict(glm_output, s = bestlam, newx = x2) 
        pred <- prediction(las_ridge_pred, testingSet$quality)
        auc <- performance(pred, measure = 'auc')@y.values[[1]]
        return(auc)
    }
}

Overall Best Model¶

The model was cross validated using 10 folds on the training set. AUC was used as the measurement of performance to be the measurement of performance as previously mentioned in the forward stepwise process. Upon cross validation of the 3 models, from 3 different approaches, the Ridge model had the highest AUC however the stepwise model is just slightly below, followed by Lasso. Although the seed was set within the function to ensure the same result could be reproduced. Changing the seed would cause the performance score to vary slightly, but still indicate the best model from the cross validation is Ridge, followed by Stepwise then Lasso.

Stepwise Model¶

Advantages

The apporach of forward stepwise allowed each predictors to be compared by adding one predictor at a time if it had the highest AUC. This process of searching for all possible combination gives a good indication of which predictor is useful based on the training dataset. This reduces model complexity, and directly prepares the model to be used on the test data to identify it's prediction performance.

Distadvantages

Stepwise has many disadvantages, and this is famously noted by Altman and Andersen (1989). The coefficients produced for each of the predictors that are not exluded are biased towards to training data, hence they are much larger than what they are meant to be. Nevertheless this method of stepwise was done using the concept of AUC, and keeping on the predictors that have the highest AUC. When refering back to the best model produced by this, density was not included. Hence it causes an issue of colinearity, as density is highly correlated with alcohol and residual sugar, in which both of these predictors are included, the removal of density could have affected the prediction of the test error of the model.

Ridge Model¶

Advantages

Although ridge is not a method of variable selection, it adds a regularization term to the regression, hence shrinking the coefficient and overall reducing the chance of overfitting. This decreases both variance and bias in the prediction performance. Another advantage is that if there are synergy between variable, such as that there are predictors that are collinear, ridge regression does not disregard the relationship between those predictors by removing them. However as colinearity creates a problem where the variance of the parameter ends up being large, ridge introduces bias to reduce the large varaince.

Distadvantages

A major disadvantage of ridge is although it applies regularization term to shrink the coefficient of the model, it does not remove them, hence why it is not a method for variable selection. This leads to a higher chance of the model being overfitting when compared to lasso or the forward stepwise approach. Nevertheless the model can also become highly complex in interpretation, as the number of predictors increases.

Lasso Model¶

Advantages

One of the major advatange of Lasso, unlike ridge, is that it helps select the variable for the final model. When the number of predictors are large, intepreting is difficult. However as lasso makes the coefficient 0 for the least important variables, the interpretation is not an issue.

Distadvantages

One of the issue with this penalization approach is that as it converges predictors that are deemed to be irrelavent to 0. It could be that the variable are actually important in the test dataset. Also, in the final model of lasso, using the corresponding seed as indicated, it showed that density was removed. Upon looking at the scatterplot matrix, density has a strong relationship with alcohol and residual sugar, as well as some relationship with total sulfur dioxide. This issue of multicollinearity, occurs within Lasso as it tends to penalize one of the predictor that is highly correlated with another, in this case it was density. The synergy between predictors should be removed as a group or selected as a set.

Best Model - Ridge¶

All three approaches were fitted onto the provided testing set in order to determine its prediction performance, AUC. As shown in the table above, stepwise had the smallest AUC. This would be due to that some variables that were removed were infact important in the testing set. Ridge and Lasso were not far off, both giving similar results, however ridge outperformed Lasso. This is most likely due to the fact that although Ridge kept all of the predictors, it also kept the predictors that are colinear with one another, but still penalising them accordinaly. This would cause a slight improvement to the prediction performance when compared to lasso.
